{"key":"processedPost-13359594","value":{"id":13359594,"first":13346978,"last":13359733,"when":1287544326,"utime":"10/20/10 06:12 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>total said:</b><br />I was just pointing out that you have massive heating, not cooling...<br />Thats why your jars steam dry <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/frown.gif\" alt=\":frown:\" title=\":frown:\"/><br /></blockquote><br /><br />Not exactly.&nbsp; It's pressure related, and it causes cooling.<br /><br />At 15 psi, the temperature inside the pressure cooker is 250F/120C, and the temperature inside the jars after 1 to 1 1/2 hours will also be 250F/120C.&nbsp; We all know that water boils at 212F/100C.&nbsp; The reason the water doesn't boil out of the jars at 120C/250F is because of the pressure.&nbsp; Release the pressure in the PC, but guess what?&nbsp; The jars are still at 15 psi inside, but less on the outside.&nbsp; This results in the moisture in the grains turning to steam, and rapidly leaving the jars.<br /><br />Now, as pressure is released, heat is released, causing a rapid cooling of the glass.&nbsp; It's like holding the nozzle down on a can of paint, or releasing propane from a tank.&nbsp; In both cases pressure is being released, and the object gets cold very rapidly.&nbsp; With glass, this results in breakage, which is what often happens when one releases the pressure.&nbsp; Another is as said above, it ruins the filter.&nbsp; Either the steam rushing out the filter gets it dirty, creating a path for contaminants, or it separates the fibers on the microscopic scale, resulting in contaminants entering the jars.<br />RR","title":"Re: PC and WBS pressure question, did i just waste 5 hours?"}}